# Infra Handoff (Terraform & AWS)

Infrastructure changes affect real cloud resources and credentials. The agent prepares; the user executes.

## Default behavior

**Do** explain what needs to run, why, expected output, and risks. Provide copy-paste-ready commands in fenced blocks with full paths and flags.

**Don't** run `terraform apply`, `terraform destroy`, AWS CLI calls that mutate resources, or deploy scripts that touch production/staging unless the user explicitly asks the agent to run them in this turn.

**Why:** Infra mistakes are costly and often irreversible; the user must see and approve each command at the keyboard.

## When the user asks for infra help

**Do** read existing `deploy/`, `terraform/`, and workflow files first; align proposals with repo conventions. Prefer plan/dry-run commands (`terraform plan`, read-only `aws … describe/list`) when diagnosing.

**Don't** invent new infra layout, change state backends, or modify IAM/credentials without user approval.

**Why:** This repo's deploy path is documented; ad-hoc infra edits bypass review.

## Secrets and credentials

**Do** reference env var names and config keys; tell the user where to set values locally or in CI.

**Don't** read, print, commit, or guess secret values (`.env`, AWS keys, tokens).

**Why:** Leaked credentials in chat or git are worse than a delayed deploy.

## CI and deploy workflows

**Do** suggest edits to `.github/workflows/` or `deploy/` when asked, then show diff and wait for the normal commit gate.

**Don't** trigger GitHub Actions, push container images, or SSH into servers on your own initiative.

**Why:** CI/deploy triggers are gated the same way as local infra — user intent must be explicit.

## If something fails in the user's environment

**Do** help interpret error output the user pastes, narrow the fix, and propose the next command.

**Don't** retry destructive commands repeatedly or "fix forward" with broad permission changes.

**Why:** Iterative blind retries on infra often widen blast radius.
